<HEADLINE>
<P>
EARNINGS; 
</P>
<P>
CAMPEAU CORP. REPORTS LOSSES OF $190 MILLION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Campeau Corp., an ailing retailing and real estate empire, reported on Tuesday 
that its losses more than doubled in the third quarter to $190 million despite 
a 5% gain in revenue to $2.56 billion. In the same quarter a year earlier, 
Campeau lost $83 million. 
</P>
<P>
The Toronto-based company, the parent of Ralphs supermarkets in Southern 
California, has been struggling under the burden of heavy debt stemming largely 
from its $6.6-billion acquisition in May, 1988, of Federated Department Stores. 
</P>
<P>
In September, Campeau was rescued from the brink of bankruptcy by a 
$250-million loan from Olympia &amp; York Developments, and the company is 
trying to raise cash by selling its prestigious Bloomingdale's department store 
chain. None of the company's nine department store chains are in Southern 
California. 
</P>
<P>
Campeau's operating profit for the quarter ended Oct. 31 totaled $255 million, 
off 4% from $265 million a year earlier. Results from Ralphs, which has been 
remodeling many of its stores, contributed somewhat to that decline. The 
Compton-based chain, as previously reported, posted an operating profit of $38 
million, down from $41 million. Analysts say Ralphs has been sheltered from 
Campeau's struggles, however, because it has a separate debt structure and its 
own credit line. 
</P>
<P>
In an effort to sound a hopeful note, Campeau noted in a news release that its 
department stores traditionally make 50% of their yearlong profits from holiday 
shopping in the fourth quarter. Company spokesmen were not available for 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
For the first nine months of the year, Campeau has lost $390 million on revenue 
of $7.04 billion. That compares to a loss of $24 million on revenue of $5.4 
billion a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
Operating profit for the nine months was $680 million, up 56% from $437 
million. The nine- month gains in operating profit and revenue resulted from 
the Federated acquisition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
