<P>
3 FIRMS SET UP EUROPEAN AIRLINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Belgium's Sabena S.A. said today it is setting up a new airline company with 
two other European carriers, British Airways and KLM Royal Dutch Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
Sabena S.A., the holding company for the Belgian carrier, will own 60% of the 
new company, to be called Sabena World Airlines. British Airways and KLM will 
each own 20% of the new business venture and each will pay $54 million for 
their stake, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
British Airways said the new corporation will create the "first truly European 
airline." 
</P>
<P>
The new company will link the operations of the three airlines into a tight 
network allowing same-day round-trip travel between 75 European cities around 
the new Euro-hub center at Brussels' Zaventem International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
The new corporation will not affect the existing structure and operations of 
the three European airlines, nor will it result in layoffs at Sabena, the 
Belgian carrier said. 
</P>
